    "abstract": "<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>\n               <jats:p>Rank-and-file employees are becoming increasingly critical for many firms, yet we know little about how their employment dynamics matter for stock prices. We analyze new data from the individual CV\u2019s of public company employees and find that rank-and-file labor flows can be used to predict abnormal stock returns. Accounting data and survey evidence indicate that workers\u2019 labor market decisions reflect information about future corporate earnings. Investors, however, do not appear to fully incorporate this information into their earnings expectations. The findings support the hypothesis that rank-and-file employees\u2019 entry and exit decisions reveal valuable insights into their employers\u2019 future stock performance.</jats:p>",
